text.p: *The Australian 10-year bond futures contract continues to find support at around 92.930, holding its ground against a weakening U.S. Treasury market and a nervous local short-end.
*However, the contract was again repelled at 92.990.
*U.S. sees late selling,despite successful 5-year note sale.
The September Australian 10-year bond futures contract continues to find support at around 92.930, holding its ground against a weakening U.S. Treasury market and a nervous local short-end.
The contract ended the SYCOM session at 92.945 and unchanged from Wednesday's pit close, although it was repelled once again at around 92.995.
This level is proving a stiff resistance area and a further barrier is expected at 93.015 before the market can re-test last week's 3-1/4 year high of 93.090, analysts said.

The local short end got a touch of the jitters late on Wednesday after an influential U.S. investment house said in a client circular that it was now neutral on three-year bonds rather than bullish, although still put a further monetary policy easing as a 75 percent chance.
The subsequent sell-off in three-year bonds also filtered to bill futures and saw the September contract wind back to 94.75 before making a partial recovery in SYCOM to 94.80.
While below a recent contract high of 94.92, at the SYCOM close it still equated to a cash rate of 5.20 percent against current 5.5 percent official interest rates.
The Reserve Bank of Australia holds its monthly board meeting next Tuesday.
Meanwhile, U.S. Treasuries succumbed to a late sell-off amid rumoured central bank selling, and despite a successful US$11.5 billion five-year note auction.
